00:02:57.840 --> 00:02:59.250
So the polar regions.

00:02:59.250 --> 00:03:02.150
We use words like the "polar
regions of the cryosphere,"

00:03:02.150 --> 00:03:04.080
so I wanted to just have a
couple slides at the beginning

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:07.770
to put us all in the same page
about what we're talking about.

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:11.440
There's two main pieces
to the cryosphere.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:13.800
Once is glaciers and ice sheets,

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:15.700
and they're formed
by accumulating snow.

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:17.460
It's so cold in Antarctica
and Greenland

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:19.060
that it rarely melts very much,

00:03:19.060 --> 00:03:21.160
and so snow just
accumulated year after year,

00:03:21.160 --> 00:03:23.860
decade after decade,
thousands of years at a time.

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:25.190
It doesn't snow very
much down there.

00:03:25.190 --> 00:03:26.900
It's a polar desert.

00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:29.430
But it doesn't melt,
so it just builds up.

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:32.620
These ice sheets can
be 4,000 meters thick.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:35.060
You might have heard about
ice coring projects that drill

00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:39.180
down through the ice sheets
to collect ice that fell

00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:41.240
as snow tens of thousands
or hundreds

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:42.800
of thousands of years ago.

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:44.800
That's the kind of
place they come from.

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:46.100
They move.

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:47.400
They move really slowly though.

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:50.790
They deform under gravity,
just like pancake batter.

00:03:50.790 --> 00:03:52.090
When you pour it on the pan,

00:03:52.090 --> 00:03:53.770
it kind of slides
out towards the edge.

00:03:53.770 --> 00:03:56.340
But they don't move
very quickly.

00:03:56.340 --> 00:03:57.640
In the middle of the ice sheet,

00:03:57.640 --> 00:04:01.160
it might move just a few
meters a year, sometimes less.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:03.280
They lose mass.

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:04.900
So they gain mass by snow fall.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:08.510
They lose mass by
generally calving icebergs

00:04:08.510 --> 00:04:10.030
at the edges of Antarctica.

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:12.790
Whenever there's a big one, it
always seems to make the news.

00:04:12.790 --> 00:04:15.790
Recently there was a square
one somebody took a picture of,

00:04:15.790 --> 00:04:17.270
and so we got phone calls
about, what do you think

00:04:17.270 --> 00:04:18.570
about this square iceberg.

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:20.060
And I'm like, it's square?

00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:21.930
I mean, what do you
want me to say?

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:23.950
[laughter] It's a
thing that happens.

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:27.020
In Greenland, it's warmer,
so actually about half

00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:28.600
of the mass lost
there is due to melt.

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:32.370
So the iceberg that sank the
Titanic almost certainly came

00:04:32.370 --> 00:04:34.810
from Greenland, and
it does calve,

00:04:34.810 --> 00:04:37.500
but it also melts
quite a lot down there.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:38.800
The other main piece

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:40.620
of the cryosphere we'll
talk about is sea ice.

00:04:40.620 --> 00:04:43.560
Now, sea ice is different
than glaciers or ice sheets.

00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:46.500
Sea ice is formed by
freezing of ocean water.

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:50.080
So the air temperature
gets cold, that will freeze

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:51.510
that top layer of water,

00:04:51.510 --> 00:04:54.640
just like you might see a
frozen lake or a frozen pond.

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:57.610
But in the ocean, it's
much more dynamic.

00:04:57.610 --> 00:05:00.500
There's tides, there's
wind, there's waves.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:03.470
And so the sea ice moves
around quite a lot.

00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:06.540
It's much thinner than glaciers.

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:10.680
It only, at its maximum, gets up
to about 20 meters or so thick.

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:13.390
In the upper left, you can see
there's some really freshly

00:05:13.390 --> 00:05:15.360
formed sea ice and
the wind has caused it

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:17.230
to raft on top of each other.

00:05:17.230 --> 00:05:20.620
You see -- if I can get
my pointer going here --

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:22.470
see areas where it's
overlapping.

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:25.130
You see places where there's
open water between it.

00:05:25.130 --> 00:05:29.230
And if that sea ice is
allowed to continue to grow,

00:05:29.230 --> 00:05:31.870
it'll start to collect
snow fall on top of it,

00:05:31.870 --> 00:05:35.100
and so that surface will turn
from a dark or translucent

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:39.170
to a bright white, as it
collects snow on top of it.

00:05:39.170 --> 00:05:40.560
Sea ice melts seasonally.

00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:43.980
When the weather gets warm
in the Artic or Antarctic,

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:46.920
sea ice extent shrinks and then
it grows again the next fall

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:48.220
and winter.

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:52.260
And it pretty much forms --
well, anywhere it's cold enough

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:55.520
to freeze the water, so places
like Hudson Bay get sea ice.

00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:59.030
A few years ago, the Great Lakes
froze over almost entirely.

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:00.330
Of course, they're freshwater,

00:06:00.330 --> 00:06:01.880
so they have a different
freezing point.

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:06.010
But around the Arctic Ocean and
around the Antarctic continent,

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:08.080
you get sea ice annually.

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:10.920
So those are the two terms
I'm going to end up using

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:12.770
that I wanted to
make sure I defined.

00:06:12.770 --> 00:06:17.010
So why is NASA interested
in these kind of areas?

00:06:17.010 --> 00:06:20.830
You might know that places
like Greenland are losing mass.

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:23.150
The Greenland ice sheet
is getting smaller.

00:06:23.150 --> 00:06:26.600
And what we've learned over the
last 10 years or so is that most

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:28.070
of that mass lost from Greenland

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:30.230
or from Antarctica
is concentrated

00:06:30.230 --> 00:06:32.210
at the edges of the ice sheet.

00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:33.510
Now, it turns out
these are the places

00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:35.990
where ocean interacts
with the ice sheets.

00:06:35.990 --> 00:06:39.940
These glaciers tend to terminate
in water, in the ocean water.

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:42.580
So as ocean water gets
just a little bit warmer,

00:06:42.580 --> 00:06:44.570
that's a large amount
of heat that's available

00:06:44.570 --> 00:06:46.740
for melting more ice.

00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:48.380
So this is a map of Greenland

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:50.350
and where we've seen
changes there.

00:06:50.350 --> 00:06:53.930
In Antarctic, here's
a time series

00:06:53.930 --> 00:06:56.500
from a mission called "GRACE."

00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:59.790
And what GRACE does is it
measures the mass change

00:06:59.790 --> 00:07:01.630
of the whole ice sheet,
and I'll talk about that

00:07:01.630 --> 00:07:02.960
in a little more detail.

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:05.210
But the take-away here
is that through time --

00:07:05.210 --> 00:07:08.120
so you can see time
marching forward here --

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:11.720
you can look at the record of
mass loss measured by GRACE.

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:14.050
Most of the loss is
here in West Antarctica.

00:07:14.050 --> 00:07:16.520
You might have heard about
places like Pine Island Glacier

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:19.390
or Thwaites Glacier
that are losing mass.

00:07:19.390 --> 00:07:23.870
And that's a place where
the ocean water contacts the

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:25.170
ice sheet.

00:07:25.170 --> 00:07:26.470
So as that ocean water
warms just a little bit,

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:28.700
it has a big impact
on the ice sheet.

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:30.860
So this place over here
is called West Antarctica.

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:32.790
This little thumb
is the peninsula.

00:07:32.790 --> 00:07:35.460
And the bigger piece
here is East Antarctica.

00:07:35.460 --> 00:07:38.310
East Antarctica is probably
three-quarters or so

00:07:38.310 --> 00:07:41.480
of the total amount
of ice in Antarctica.

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:45.930
And it doesn't change nearly as
quickly as West Antarctica does.

00:07:45.930 --> 00:07:49.190
So that's one reason
why NASA is interested,

00:07:49.190 --> 00:07:51.590
because these ice
sheets are changing

00:07:51.590 --> 00:07:55.700
and they're losing mass,
and that mass, that water,

00:07:55.700 --> 00:07:57.350
when it leaves the ice
sheet, it just goes back

00:07:57.350 --> 00:07:58.650
into the world's oceans.

00:07:58.650 --> 00:08:00.670
And that's one of
the main contributors

00:08:00.670 --> 00:08:02.350
to global sea level rise.

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:05.030
You took ice that used to be
sitting on rock in Antarctica

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:08.080
or Greenland, you put the
ice cubes back in the water,

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:10.670
and they're going
to raise sea level.

00:08:10.670 --> 00:08:13.390
So that's one of the main
reasons NASA's interested.

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:16.530
For sea ice, if I can
get this guy to play.

00:08:16.530 --> 00:08:20.120
We talked about how sea
ice is pretty dynamic.

00:08:20.120 --> 00:08:24.380
And in this animation, you
see time marching past up here

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:26.910
in the upper left,
and these are images

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:28.860
of the sea ice extent
in the Arctic Ocean.

00:08:28.860 --> 00:08:32.260
You can see Greenland over here,
Alaska over here, Canada here.

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:33.560
And this should give you a sense

00:08:33.560 --> 00:08:35.720
for just how dynamic
that sea ice is.

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:39.510
It grows and shrinks annually,
and when storms come through,

00:08:39.510 --> 00:08:41.130
it moves it quite a lot.

00:08:41.130 --> 00:08:43.680
You can see it generally tends
to form over in this part

00:08:43.680 --> 00:08:46.840
of the basin and is lost
right down the coast

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:48.140
of Greenland over here.

00:08:48.140 --> 00:08:50.810
You also lose some
over in this area.

00:08:50.810 --> 00:08:55.430
And we've been able to take
pictures of sea ice extent

00:08:55.430 --> 00:08:57.740
from imagers, since about 1979.

00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:00.240
So that's how we put
together this time series

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:03.040
of how the extent
has been changing.

00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:04.540
Now, one of the things
we're really interested

00:09:04.540 --> 00:09:07.140
in is how the thickness
of sea ice changes.

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:09.170
Really thick sea ice,
it's hard to break up.

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:12.130
It lasts much longer
than very thin sea ice.

00:09:12.130 --> 00:09:15.190
If it's first-year sea ice,
you have a storm come through,

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:17.460
it can break up that ice.

00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:20.000
And what happens when
you lose sea ice is

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.250
that it increases
the transfer of heat

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.710
from the ocean to
the atmosphere.

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:29.030
And you say, all right, well,
why would we care about that?

00:09:29.030 --> 00:09:31.430
It turns out that the
exchange of heat from the ocean

00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:33.460
to the atmosphere in the
Arctic is one of the big things

00:09:33.460 --> 00:09:35.620
that drives climate patterns

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:37.280
and weather patterns
around the world.

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:39.550
Things like the jet stream
position is influenced

00:09:39.550 --> 00:09:41.720
by the heat exchange up here.

00:09:41.720 --> 00:09:46.300
Whether we have a snowier winter
here in D.C. is determined,

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:49.080
in part, by the state of
the sea ice in the Arctic.

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:50.380
So that's really a driver

00:09:50.380 --> 00:09:52.220
for weather patterns
around the world.

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:55.360
So the more we can understand
about how it grows in shrinks,

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:56.910
including the thickness,
the better.

00:09:56.910 --> 00:10:00.780
Oop -- and I'm going
to go to the next one.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:02.080
There we go.

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:05.390
So if we just look at the area
of Arctic sea ice in September

00:10:05.390 --> 00:10:07.170
of every year, we can
make a time series

00:10:07.170 --> 00:10:08.970
for how the extent has changed.

00:10:08.970 --> 00:10:11.250
We've picked September because
that's basically the end

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:13.260
of the summer season
in the Arctic.

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:16.220
You get into October, it gets
cold, sea ice starts to regrow.

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:17.850
So what we're looking
at here is a graph

00:10:17.850 --> 00:10:20.090
of the minimum sea ice
extent in the Arctic.

00:10:20.090 --> 00:10:22.520
It's usually about the
second week of September.

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:25.620
And what you can see is
that since 1979 here,

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:27.890
it was kind of flat
for a most of the '80s,

00:10:27.890 --> 00:10:29.190
but you get into the '90s

00:10:29.190 --> 00:10:30.910
and you get bigger
and bigger changes.

00:10:30.910 --> 00:10:32.210
And now we're -- oop.

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:33.510
I should put the new one in.

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:34.810
Now we're out here in 2016,

00:10:34.810 --> 00:10:36.600
there's actually two more
data points on there.

00:10:36.600 --> 00:10:40.080
It's a lot smaller than
it was back in the '80s.

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:41.700
And remember, this
is the extent.

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:43.490
This doesn't tell us
anything about the thickness

00:10:43.490 --> 00:10:44.790
or the stability of it.

00:10:44.790 --> 00:10:47.050
It's just how much was there.

00:10:47.050 --> 00:10:49.710
The mission I work on is called
ICESat-2 and it's designed

00:10:49.710 --> 00:10:52.760
to measure that thickness
of the sea ice.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:55.920
In the Antarctic, the
seas around the Antarctic,

00:10:55.920 --> 00:10:58.190
the changes are much
more subtle.

00:10:58.190 --> 00:11:00.780
The graph up here is the
change in the Arctic,

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:02.120
which we just saw a moment ago.

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:03.770
For the Antarctic,
it's pretty flat.

00:11:03.770 --> 00:11:05.180
It might be increasing
a little bit.

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:06.550
You can see there's
been this change

00:11:06.550 --> 00:11:08.120
in about the last
four or five years.

00:11:08.120 --> 00:11:10.220
It's hard to know if
that's something permanent

00:11:10.220 --> 00:11:11.540
or short-term.

00:11:11.540 --> 00:11:15.820
But at least since the early
'80s, since 1980 or so,

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:17.670
Antarctic extent has
been pretty flat.

00:11:17.670 --> 00:11:22.740
The Arctic has been losing
sea ice area over time.

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:24.160
So that's why NASA's interested.

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:25.460
One of their mandates is

00:11:25.460 --> 00:11:27.760
to understand the
planet we live on, Earth,

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:31.740
and the cryosphere is
a big piece of that.

00:11:31.740 --> 00:11:33.540
So as I mentioned, we
have two new missions

00:11:33.540 --> 00:11:35.110
to study the cryosphere.

00:11:35.110 --> 00:11:37.540
GRACE-Follow-On, its launch
is up here in the upper left,

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:39.480
launched in May of this year.

00:11:39.480 --> 00:11:43.310
And the mission I work on,
ICESat-2, just launched about --

00:11:43.310 --> 00:11:45.290
not even two months ago.

00:11:45.290 --> 00:11:47.110
We launched in the
early morning hours,

00:11:47.110 --> 00:11:50.450
so we had a really nice
view of the rocket.

00:11:50.450 --> 00:11:53.130
GRACE-Follow-On launched
in the afternoon.

00:11:53.130 --> 00:11:54.430
Both from the West Coast,

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:57.630
Vandenberg Air Force
Base out in California.

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:01.360
So GRACE-Follow-On.

00:12:01.360 --> 00:12:02.720
As you might imagine
from the name,

00:12:02.720 --> 00:12:04.420
there was an original
mission called GRACE.

00:12:04.420 --> 00:12:05.920
We saw some of its data earlier.

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:08.270
This is the Follow-On
mission to that.

00:12:08.270 --> 00:12:11.100
And GRACE and GRACE-Follow-On
are composed of two satellites.

00:12:11.100 --> 00:12:12.400
You can see the one
in the foreground,

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:14.680
and there's another one way
off here in the background.

00:12:14.680 --> 00:12:17.850
And what the mission does
is it measures the distance

00:12:17.850 --> 00:12:20.970
between those two
satellites very accurately.

00:12:20.970 --> 00:12:23.320
It uses microwave
ranging between them.

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:26.600
So it can range to better a
millimeter how far apart these

00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:28.150
two satellites are.

00:12:28.150 --> 00:12:31.480
And the way it works is that
as the lead satellite goes

00:12:31.480 --> 00:12:34.190
over a place in the earth
that has relatively more mass

00:12:34.190 --> 00:12:37.450
or less mass, it experiences
a slight acceleration

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:39.290
and it moves a little
farther away

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:41.070
from the trailing satellite.

00:12:41.070 --> 00:12:42.910
Now, when the trailing
satellite gets up to that place

00:12:42.910 --> 00:12:45.620
where there's a little more
mass, it also accelerates,

00:12:45.620 --> 00:12:48.990
and so the distance
between the two is a measure

00:12:48.990 --> 00:12:53.000
of how much mass difference
there is in the earth.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.560
So over Antarctica, when the
Antarctic ice sheet is losing

00:12:56.560 --> 00:13:00.990
mass, we compile data
from many passes of GRACE

00:13:00.990 --> 00:13:04.460
over the same places in
Antarctica to determine,

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:06.550
is it gaining mass
or is it losing mass?

00:13:06.550 --> 00:13:08.740
Is the front satellite
accelerating just a little bit

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:10.700
more than it was last time,
or maybe a little less

00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:12.880
than it was last time?

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:16.220
GRACE was mainly designed to
study the hydrologic cycle.

00:13:16.220 --> 00:13:19.820
It can do things like
measure aquifers.

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:22.350
Are we losing water out of
aquifers or are we gaining it?

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:24.810
Is there more mass here,
is there less mass here?

00:13:24.810 --> 00:13:27.290
It can measure changes
in seasonal snow,

00:13:27.290 --> 00:13:31.470
which is totally cool, because
you get a big snowfall here

00:13:31.470 --> 00:13:33.740
and you could measure
that in GRACE data.

00:13:33.740 --> 00:13:35.990
So what GRACE is doing
is measuring mass

00:13:35.990 --> 00:13:38.150
changes primarily.

00:13:38.150 --> 00:13:43.140
Given that, it's on orbit 350
kilometers above the surface

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:46.860
of the earth and these two
satellites are hundreds

00:13:46.860 --> 00:13:48.280
of kilometers apart.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:51.380
You end up with a pretty low
spatial resolution measurement.

00:13:51.380 --> 00:13:54.390
And what I mean by that is you
can measure mass changes really

00:13:54.390 --> 00:13:56.320
accurately, but only an average

00:13:56.320 --> 00:13:59.340
over hundreds of
square kilometers.

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:01.730
So it's an average
over a big area.

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:04.780
However, given its orbit, you
get a lot of data through time.

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:06.460
So you can get a data
point over a place

00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:08.920
about once a month,
which is great.

00:14:08.920 --> 00:14:11.640
We saw that time series earlier
of mass change in Antarctica

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:14.740
from GRACE and that was a data
point about once every month.

00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:17.910
GRACE and GRACE-Follow-On are
by NASA's Jet Propulsion Lab

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:22.000
out in Pasadena, California,
and that's all I'm going to say

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.030
about GRACE, because I work at
one of the other NASA centers,

00:14:25.030 --> 00:14:26.930
right out here in Maryland,

00:14:26.930 --> 00:14:29.520
NASA's Goddard Space
Flight Center.

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:32.740
And we recently launched
ICESat-2.

00:14:32.740 --> 00:14:35.850
Now, at ICESat-2, as you might
imagine, is also a follow-on.

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:38.120
There was a first
ICESat mission,

00:14:38.120 --> 00:14:39.420
although it'd be pretty bold

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:42.150
to name your first mission
ICESat-2, just to mix it

00:14:42.150 --> 00:14:43.800
up and confuse people.

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:45.620
[laughter] We didn't do that.

00:14:45.620 --> 00:14:49.280
ICESat-2 is a laser altimeter,
so it has a laser on board.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:52.930
And what it does is it sends out
a small pulse of laser light,

00:14:52.930 --> 00:14:56.020
and it times, super accurately,
how long it takes that light

00:14:56.020 --> 00:15:00.970
to go from the space craft
to the earth and back again.

00:15:00.970 --> 00:15:03.700
So that's essentially a range.

00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:06.960
And what it does with that
is we reconstruct elevation

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:09.060
of the earth's surface.

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:12.270
We do that by taking that time,
how long did it take to go

00:15:12.270 --> 00:15:15.730
from space craft to the
earth and back again,

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:18.230
figuring out where we were
pointing or am I pointing

00:15:18.230 --> 00:15:19.530
at the wall over here?

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:20.830
Am I pointing at
the wall over there?

00:15:20.830 --> 00:15:22.220
And where are we in the orbit?

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:23.860
You put those three
pieces together

00:15:23.860 --> 00:15:26.120
and you can measure the height
of anything you fly over,

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:28.780
just by bouncing
these laser beams off.

00:15:28.780 --> 00:15:31.360
The footprint size of the
laser beam on the ground is

00:15:31.360 --> 00:15:34.920
about 17 meters, so sort
of the size of this room.

00:15:34.920 --> 00:15:36.940
So we get really
detailed information.

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:39.990
We can measure the height of
something about this size.

00:15:39.990 --> 00:15:43.000
Whereas GRACE was over
hundreds of square kilometers,

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.800
we're measuring meter scale.

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:49.580
However, we have fairly
low resolution temporally.

00:15:49.580 --> 00:15:51.580
We've got these little
spots on the ground,

00:15:51.580 --> 00:15:54.280
and our orbit repeats
about every 91 days.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:57.610
So we can see about times a
year how a particular place

00:15:57.610 --> 00:15:59.300
is changing.

00:15:59.300 --> 00:16:01.420
Together, these two
missions, GRACE-Follow-On

00:16:01.420 --> 00:16:03.590
and ICESat-2 are
really complimentary.

00:16:03.590 --> 00:16:05.330
One gives you great
time resolution,

00:16:05.330 --> 00:16:07.220
the other gives you
great spatial resolution.

00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:09.940
You put those two things
together, you we should be able

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:12.400
to learn more about how ice
sheets and sea ice are changing

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:14.770
than we've ever been
able to before.

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:17.880
So I'm going to walk you
through a little bit more

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:19.940
about how ICESat-2 works.

00:16:19.940 --> 00:16:22.200
The main instrument on
here is called the lidar.

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:24.280
That's the thing that
generates the laser light.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:27.770
And the time it takes to go
from space craft to ground

00:16:27.770 --> 00:16:29.540
and back again, we call
a range measurement.

00:16:29.540 --> 00:16:31.740
It's essentially a distance.

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:33.640
The other piece we need
is the pointing angle.

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:35.020
Are we pointing straight down?

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:36.320
Are we a little left?

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:37.620
Are we a little right?

00:16:37.620 --> 00:16:39.840
And then the last piece is
where are we in the orbit?

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:41.830
Are we over Maryland
or are we over Canada,

00:16:41.830 --> 00:16:43.170
or are we over Greenland?

00:16:43.170 --> 00:16:44.680
And we figure that out with GPS,

00:16:44.680 --> 00:16:46.220
just like you would
in your phone.

00:16:46.220 --> 00:16:48.380
Certainly, these are
much fancier GPSs

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:50.690
and give us much
more accurate data

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:52.020
than you would get from a phone.

00:16:52.020 --> 00:16:54.420
But basically, you take these
three pieces: pointing angle,

00:16:54.420 --> 00:16:56.820
range measurement, space
craft altitude, and you figure

00:16:56.820 --> 00:16:58.120
out the height of the earth.

00:16:58.120 --> 00:17:00.820
If you measure that height at
the same place through time,

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:03.900
you can tell, is it getting
higher or is it getting lower?

00:17:03.900 --> 00:17:05.690
From the vantage point of space,

00:17:05.690 --> 00:17:07.500
you can see how ice
sheets are changing,

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:12.420
how sea ice is changing, oceans,
deserts, forests, all of it,

00:17:12.420 --> 00:17:13.810
which is totally cool.

00:17:13.810 --> 00:17:19.160
A couple of slides
about technical details,

00:17:19.160 --> 00:17:20.930
in case anybody is interested.

00:17:20.930 --> 00:17:25.440
The laser on ICESat-2 fires
10,000 shots a second,

00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:28.530
which is an incredibly
fast repetition rate.

00:17:28.530 --> 00:17:33.060
And it sends out really small
pulses of light, so micropulses,

00:17:33.060 --> 00:17:37.010
we would call them, in each
of six beams simultaneously.

00:17:37.010 --> 00:17:40.230
That's the multibeam
part of it there.

00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:43.380
And the way it does its
detection and its measurement,

00:17:43.380 --> 00:17:45.970
it sends out these light pulses
of light 10,000 times a second,

00:17:45.970 --> 00:17:48.160
and it's actually
detecting individual photons

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:49.460
as they come back.

00:17:49.460 --> 00:17:51.420
So we have super
sensitive detectors on board

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:53.580
for each of those six spots.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:55.070
So people say, oh, you know,

00:17:55.070 --> 00:17:58.530
could I see the laser
light from the space craft?

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:02.510
Probably not, because they're
so low energy and the number

00:18:02.510 --> 00:18:05.040
of photons that we're detecting
on the way back from each

00:18:05.040 --> 00:18:08.390
of these shots is
kind of 1, 2, 3, 4.

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:11.100
It's really small number
of photons coming back in,

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:13.970
but that's the basis
of our measurement.

00:18:13.970 --> 00:18:17.660
With this super fast firing
laser and our altitude,

00:18:17.660 --> 00:18:20.340
we get a footprint
that's about 17 meters

00:18:20.340 --> 00:18:25.790
in diameter every 70 centimeters
along each of those 6 beams.

00:18:25.790 --> 00:18:27.140
So the footprint from one shot

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:31.380
to the next overlaps the
previous one by about 95%.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:33.360
So we end up with
continuous coverage

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:35.090
in the along-track direction.

00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:36.600
It's a tremendous
amount of data.

00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:39.420
And it's a very NASA way of
measuring things, you know?

00:18:39.420 --> 00:18:42.190
It's a laser in space,
10,000 times a second,

00:18:42.190 --> 00:18:44.280
counting individual photons.

00:18:44.280 --> 00:18:45.890
It's kind of crazy.

00:18:45.890 --> 00:18:48.910
And the cool thing is, is that
later in the presentation,

00:18:48.910 --> 00:18:50.210
I'll be able to show
you what some

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:51.520
of our early data looks like.

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:53.940
We've been on orbit now
for about six weeks.

00:18:53.940 --> 00:18:55.720
We're still in calibration
phase,

00:18:55.720 --> 00:18:58.400
but it's astounding
what you can see

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:01.260
with this kind of instrument.

00:19:01.260 --> 00:19:04.170
The last slide about
technical details is here.

00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:06.690
If you were able to see each of
these six spots on the ground,

00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:10.470
you'd see that we've arranged
them in a rectangular pattern,

00:19:10.470 --> 00:19:13.590
so that as the beams are
described on the surface

00:19:13.590 --> 00:19:15.850
of the earth, we have
these beam pairs.

00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:17.590
We have two beams right
next to each other,

00:19:17.590 --> 00:19:20.040
separated by about 90 meters.

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:23.160
And what that does for us is it
lets us measure the elevation

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:25.660
in the along-track
direction, sure.

00:19:25.660 --> 00:19:27.570
But it also lets us
measure the slope

00:19:27.570 --> 00:19:29.070
in the across-track direction.

00:19:29.070 --> 00:19:30.980
Is this one higher than
that one, or vice versa?

00:19:30.980 --> 00:19:33.370
And it turns out that's
a key piece in figuring

00:19:33.370 --> 00:19:36.480
out how ice sheet
elevations are changing.

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:41.440
So we have six beams
arranged in three beam pairs.

00:19:41.440 --> 00:19:44.390
And if anybody's interested in
what wavelength we're using,

00:19:44.390 --> 00:19:47.850
it's a bright green
light, 532 nanometers.

00:19:47.850 --> 00:19:49.950
We split it into
six beams, and yeah,

00:19:49.950 --> 00:19:52.290
we're detecting individual
photons as they come in.

00:19:52.290 --> 00:19:54.640
I realize that for folks
who don't work on this kind

00:19:54.640 --> 00:19:56.420
of thing, it all sounds
a little bit esoteric.

00:19:56.420 --> 00:20:00.350
So we actually have a
little animation that --

00:20:00.350 --> 00:20:02.510
that really brings it home,
what this is all about.

00:20:02.510 --> 00:20:06.860
So let's see if I can
get this thing to play.

00:20:06.860 --> 00:20:08.160
Doo-doo-doo.

