00:22:56.080 --> 00:22:58.010
So ICESat-2 is in orbit now.

00:22:58.010 --> 00:23:00.880
Our orbit takes us up to
88 degrees north and down

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:03.570
to 88 degrees south,
and we do about 15 laps

00:23:03.570 --> 00:23:04.870
of the planet every day.

00:23:04.870 --> 00:23:06.260
Can you guys see this okay?

00:23:06.260 --> 00:23:08.030
From my perspective, it's
a little bit washed out,

00:23:08.030 --> 00:23:10.480
but you can see it cruising
around the planet there.

00:23:10.480 --> 00:23:13.320
You'll notice there's lots
of clouds on Earth, right?

00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:14.840
You go outside, maybe
it's a sunny day,

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:16.280
maybe it's a cloudy day.

00:23:16.280 --> 00:23:21.490
We're using really low
energy visible green light.

00:23:21.490 --> 00:23:23.250
So on a cloudy day,
we're mostly going

00:23:23.250 --> 00:23:25.090
to measure the tops
of the clouds.

00:23:25.090 --> 00:23:26.390
The light will bounce
off the clouds.

00:23:26.390 --> 00:23:28.750
You might have seen
that in the last video,

00:23:28.750 --> 00:23:30.970
where some of the
photons got scattered

00:23:30.970 --> 00:23:32.610
by the clouds or bounced back.

00:23:32.610 --> 00:23:34.350
They didn't make it all
the way to the ground.

00:23:34.350 --> 00:23:37.120
But places where we
have a clear sky view,

00:23:37.120 --> 00:23:40.810
we'll detect photons coming back
from the surface of the earth.

00:23:40.810 --> 00:23:44.250
We're called ICESat-2 so the
instrument really is optimized

00:23:44.250 --> 00:23:49.570
to measure changes in sea ice
and in glaciers and ice sheets.

00:23:49.570 --> 00:23:51.620
But from space, as
I mentioned earlier,

00:23:51.620 --> 00:23:54.210
we really do get a
measurement of everything.

00:23:54.210 --> 00:23:56.460
We'll get lots of
data over the oceans.

00:23:56.460 --> 00:23:59.610
We'll get lots of data
over land, over cities.

00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:03.850
And we have data products that
cover each one of those things.

00:24:03.850 --> 00:24:08.180
The data product I work on,
the goal of that product is

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:12.580
to generate unique latitude,
longitude, and elevation

00:24:12.580 --> 00:24:15.240
for each photon that we detect.

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:19.070
So with a laser firing
10,000 times a second,

00:24:19.070 --> 00:24:22.140
six beams at the same time,

00:24:22.140 --> 00:24:24.870
order of about five
photons coming back,

00:24:24.870 --> 00:24:26.350
something like that.

00:24:26.350 --> 00:24:29.120
So one way to think about it
is that in the time it takes

00:24:29.120 --> 00:24:32.210
to blink about half a second,
ICESat-2 will do on the order

00:24:32.210 --> 00:24:35.910
of about 15 or 20,000 individual
measurements of photons.

00:24:35.910 --> 00:24:37.790
So it's a tremendous
amount of data.

00:24:37.790 --> 00:24:39.710
The laser is on 24/7.

00:24:39.710 --> 00:24:42.380
It's on all the time,
collecting data.

00:24:42.380 --> 00:24:44.820
So these data products are big.

00:24:44.820 --> 00:24:46.780
If you're interested
in ice sheet elevation

00:24:46.780 --> 00:24:48.080
and ice sheet elevation
exchange,

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:50.180
you probably don't want
to deal with, you know,

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:52.260
billions of individual photons.

00:24:52.260 --> 00:24:54.610
You're going to average
those together.

00:24:54.610 --> 00:24:57.480
Or similarly, if you're
interested in tree height,

00:24:57.480 --> 00:24:59.560
you don't want to deal with
things at the photon level.

00:24:59.560 --> 00:25:01.310
The data sets are
simply too big.

00:25:01.310 --> 00:25:04.070
So what the higher
level products do is

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:05.920
to aggregate those
photons together.

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:08.690
Maybe they'll take 40 meters
or so worth of photons

00:25:08.690 --> 00:25:12.210
or 100 meters worth of photons,
average those heights together

00:25:12.210 --> 00:25:13.970
to come up with one
elevation measurement

00:25:13.970 --> 00:25:17.640
that has much better
precision than a single photon.

