00:34:35.150 --> 00:34:38.200
The term for that is "free
board," same as a free board

00:34:38.200 --> 00:34:40.580
on a boat, if you guys
are sailors at all.

00:34:40.580 --> 00:34:43.250
But what it does for sea ice
is since we know it's ice,

00:34:43.250 --> 00:34:46.030
we know the density of it, we
know the density of the water,

00:34:46.030 --> 00:34:48.610
it lets us estimate the
thickness of that sea ice.

00:34:48.610 --> 00:34:51.680
About 10% of sea ice sticks
up out of the ocean water.

00:34:51.680 --> 00:34:54.750
So in this case, let's
say the free board

00:34:54.750 --> 00:34:57.100
of the sea ice was
about 30 centimeters.

00:34:57.100 --> 00:34:58.400
That means the total thickness

00:34:58.400 --> 00:35:01.510
of that sea ice is
about 10 times that.

00:35:01.510 --> 00:35:03.480
It's about 3 meters.

00:35:03.480 --> 00:35:05.890
That lets us get at the
third dimension of sea ice.

00:35:05.890 --> 00:35:08.800
We can measure the extent
really readily from cameras,

00:35:08.800 --> 00:35:11.550
but getting the thickness has
been a long-standing challenge

00:35:11.550 --> 00:35:13.530
for sea ice science.

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:16.420
So with ICESat-2 data
combined with those images,

00:35:16.420 --> 00:35:19.520
we really can put together
a three-dimensional picture

00:35:19.520 --> 00:35:21.590
of the sea ice in the
Arctic, in the Antarctic,

00:35:21.590 --> 00:35:24.040
and how it's changing
through time.

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:27.130
So here's an example of what
data over sea ice look like.

00:35:27.130 --> 00:35:30.070
It's a little messier, but
what you end up seeing are all

00:35:30.070 --> 00:35:31.930
of these ridges on sea ice.

00:35:31.930 --> 00:35:33.230
That's the sea ice elevation.

00:35:33.230 --> 00:35:36.480
But can you see these little
flat spots through here?

00:35:36.480 --> 00:35:37.880
Those are cracks in the sea ice.

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:40.690
That's where we're ranging down
to the ocean in between them.

00:35:40.690 --> 00:35:43.020
So these are really small leads.

00:35:43.020 --> 00:35:44.940
Here's a scale bar
for reference.

00:35:44.940 --> 00:35:47.960
It's about 70 kilometers, so
this is a long stretch of data

00:35:47.960 --> 00:35:49.740
through the Arctic Ocean.

00:35:49.740 --> 00:35:51.650
But there's some
larger leads over here

00:35:51.650 --> 00:35:53.400
and another big one over there.

00:35:53.400 --> 00:35:55.740
So in this case, we have
the ocean water here,

00:35:55.740 --> 00:35:57.480
right about zero meters.

00:35:57.480 --> 00:36:01.330
And the sea ice here is about --
sticking up by about one meters.

00:36:01.330 --> 00:36:03.880
So that's actually really
thick, probably old sea ice.

00:36:03.880 --> 00:36:05.550
It's on the order
of ten meters thick,

00:36:05.550 --> 00:36:09.250
about ten times what you're
measuring for the free board.

00:36:09.250 --> 00:36:11.600
So from a data processing
standpoint, the challenge

00:36:11.600 --> 00:36:15.540
of sea ice data is to
separate ocean elevation

00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:18.940
from sea ice elevation so
you can do that difference.

00:36:22.040 --> 00:36:24.530
Over ice sheets, here's a
stretch from Antarctica.

00:36:24.530 --> 00:36:25.930
Here's the Ross Sea down here,

00:36:25.930 --> 00:36:28.930
Ross Ice Shelf going
up onto the plateau.

00:36:28.930 --> 00:36:30.260
Actually, this one's
going the other way.

00:36:30.260 --> 00:36:33.700
It's going from the plateau
down onto the ice sheet.

00:36:33.700 --> 00:36:36.200
Elevation-wise, ice
sheets are kind of boring.

00:36:36.200 --> 00:36:37.870
They're pretty flat.

00:36:37.870 --> 00:36:41.430
They do have some typography
to them, but not like the coast

00:36:41.430 --> 00:36:44.470
of Mexico and not like
Australia, and not like sea ice.

00:36:44.470 --> 00:36:48.160
So this data often looks
pretty flat at a short scale,

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:50.680
but at a larger scale, you start
to see mountains through there

00:36:50.680 --> 00:36:52.040
that we're ranging to.

00:36:52.040 --> 00:36:54.340
The blue line is ICESat-2 data.

00:36:54.340 --> 00:36:57.800
And this black line
that's on top of it is data

00:36:57.800 --> 00:37:01.210
from another lesser satellite
that we won't talk about.

00:37:01.210 --> 00:37:04.730
And you can see how this
black line is far inferior

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:08.180
to the super detail we're
getting from ICESat-2.

00:37:08.180 --> 00:37:10.740
The data from along the black
curve are totally missing this

00:37:10.740 --> 00:37:13.080
value right here, while
we're picking up the bottom

00:37:13.080 --> 00:37:16.630
of the valley and the little
peaks in the valley, as well.

00:37:16.630 --> 00:37:18.530
So that's totally cool.

00:37:18.530 --> 00:37:20.790
Here's another stretch
where there's some crevasses

00:37:20.790 --> 00:37:22.430
or cracks in the ice sheet.

00:37:22.430 --> 00:37:27.500
These are pretty steep sides on
these things, and we're picking

00:37:27.500 --> 00:37:30.340
up the slopes from the top all
the way down to the bottom,

00:37:30.340 --> 00:37:31.850
some data off the
bottom and back again.

00:37:31.850 --> 00:37:33.510
So we can actually
measure crevasse depth,

00:37:33.510 --> 00:37:35.050
as well, which is cool.

00:37:35.050 --> 00:37:39.190
What we really want to do though
is take data from ice sheets

00:37:39.190 --> 00:37:42.180
from the same place and
compare it through time

00:37:42.180 --> 00:37:44.890
to see how it's getting bigger
and how it's getting smaller.

00:37:44.890 --> 00:37:47.530
We think with the data
quality we're seeing so far,

00:37:47.530 --> 00:37:49.500
we should be able to
resolve elevation changes

00:37:49.500 --> 00:37:54.670
of about a centimeter,
from space, using photons.

00:37:54.670 --> 00:37:57.630
It's -- I've worked on the
project for about ten years,

00:37:57.630 --> 00:38:01.560
and you go through lots of hoops
and reviews and things go well

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:02.860
and things don't go well.

00:38:02.860 --> 00:38:05.100
But it's so gratifying to
actually see it on orbit

00:38:05.100 --> 00:38:07.340
and collecting data like that.

00:38:07.340 --> 00:38:08.860
It's really amazing.

00:38:08.860 --> 00:38:13.590
And the data quality has
been just outstanding.

00:38:13.590 --> 00:38:17.340
Knock on wood [knocking]
[laughter] Cool.

00:38:17.340 --> 00:38:19.420
So ICESat-2 is in orbit now.

00:38:19.420 --> 00:38:21.420
Here's the first known
sighting of ICESat-2.

00:38:21.420 --> 00:38:23.130
It might be a little
bit hard to see.

00:38:23.130 --> 00:38:27.590
One of our colleagues in the
lab, Jeremy, was down in Chile.

00:38:27.590 --> 00:38:30.880
He took a look at where we were
supposed to be through time

00:38:30.880 --> 00:38:33.200
and he noticed that on
October 25th at about 3:00

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:34.570
in the morning, we were
going to be very close

00:38:34.570 --> 00:38:36.160
to where he was in Chile.

00:38:36.160 --> 00:38:37.910
And so he set up his
camera on a tripod

00:38:37.910 --> 00:38:39.800
on about a 20 second exposure.

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:41.440
And I can't even see
it from my angle,

00:38:41.440 --> 00:38:43.330
but there should be a line right

00:38:43.330 --> 00:38:46.140
through here and
that's ICESat-2.

00:38:46.140 --> 00:38:48.510
That's how you know
it's not fake.

00:38:48.510 --> 00:38:51.260
[ Laughter ]

00:38:51.260 --> 00:38:52.720
You can go outside and
see it go past, right?

00:38:52.720 --> 00:38:54.030
&gt;&gt; Somebody could
draw a line of it.

00:38:54.030 --> 00:38:56.040
[ Laughter ]

00:38:56.040 --> 00:38:57.340
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann:
I encourage you

00:38:57.340 --> 00:38:58.640
to take a look at our website.

00:38:58.640 --> 00:39:00.520
You can see when we're going
to be in your neighborhood,

00:39:00.520 --> 00:39:03.070
and you can look up
at the right time.

00:39:03.070 --> 00:39:05.090
And if the sun catches
the solar array,

00:39:05.090 --> 00:39:06.400
this is exactly what you'd see.

00:39:06.400 --> 00:39:08.890
&gt;&gt; The website is
the heavens-above,

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:10.510
you can see any satellite
going over.

00:39:10.510 --> 00:39:11.810
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann:
That's right.

00:39:11.810 --> 00:39:13.110
And you can just type in
ICESat-2 and it'll tell you

00:39:13.110 --> 00:39:15.090
when your next pass is.

00:39:15.090 --> 00:39:17.500
Absolutely.

00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:20.790
Cool. So the last section I'm
going to talk about is, okay,

00:39:20.790 --> 00:39:22.980
great, we're measuring all
these elevations from space.

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:24.280
It's outstanding.

00:39:24.280 --> 00:39:25.580
Yada, yada, yada.

00:39:25.580 --> 00:39:27.470
How do you know they're right?

00:39:27.470 --> 00:39:29.610
How do we compare with
something else to say

00:39:29.610 --> 00:39:31.450
that we're getting
the right answer?

00:39:31.450 --> 00:39:35.480
So you might have noticed in
the animation of the orbits

00:39:35.480 --> 00:39:37.530
that we go up to 88
north and 88 south.

00:39:37.530 --> 00:39:42.290
And all of our tracks converge
right at 88 north and 88 south.

00:39:42.290 --> 00:39:44.290
It turns out that 88 north,
of course, is in the middle

00:39:44.290 --> 00:39:46.940
of the Arctic Ocean, kind
of a tough place to get to.

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:50.250
88 south, ironically enough,
is much easier to get to.

00:39:50.250 --> 00:39:51.610
It's pretty close
to the South Pole.

00:39:51.610 --> 00:39:55.530
It's about 220 kilometers away.

00:39:55.530 --> 00:39:57.750
And you can fly down
to the South Pole.

00:39:57.750 --> 00:39:59.970
The U.S. has a research station
right at the center there,

00:39:59.970 --> 00:40:02.480
which is what I did
last year in December

00:40:02.480 --> 00:40:03.780
with three other colleagues.

00:40:03.780 --> 00:40:08.460
And we went out to this area
to measure the elevation

00:40:08.460 --> 00:40:11.840
of the ice sheet with GPS.

00:40:11.840 --> 00:40:15.000
We flew into South Pole Station,
we took two tract vehicles

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:18.320
and drove out to this 88
south line of latitude

00:40:18.320 --> 00:40:22.700
and surveyed the elevation along
this part of the arc right here.

00:40:22.700 --> 00:40:26.510
We had two high precision
GPS instruments with us

00:40:26.510 --> 00:40:29.590
to create a reference
dataset for ICESat-2.

00:40:29.590 --> 00:40:32.690
So when we're getting data
from space, we can compare it

00:40:32.690 --> 00:40:36.420
with our GPS data to say,
well, how are we doing?

00:40:36.420 --> 00:40:39.340
And having that independent
dataset is a great check

00:40:39.340 --> 00:40:40.640
on the data.

00:40:40.640 --> 00:40:42.370
All of our tracks converge
around this circle,

00:40:42.370 --> 00:40:46.990
so as it turns out, ICESat-2
will survey this little section

00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:48.290
at least once a day

00:40:48.290 --> 00:40:50.580
and sometimes twice a
day, depending on the day.

00:40:50.580 --> 00:40:54.250
The whole circle was too
far around for us to go.

00:40:54.250 --> 00:40:56.400
We were cold and
wanted to go home.

00:40:56.400 --> 00:40:58.840
[laughter] So we only did
this 300 kilometer stretch.

00:40:58.840 --> 00:41:00.880
Actually, that's not true.

00:41:00.880 --> 00:41:02.590
It was all part of the plan.

00:41:02.590 --> 00:41:03.890
But still.

00:41:03.890 --> 00:41:06.920
[laughter] We'll intersect 277
of the tracts, it's about 20%

00:41:06.920 --> 00:41:09.050
of the ICESat-2 tracks.

00:41:09.050 --> 00:41:12.470
And yeah, we're getting
about one centimeter accuracy

00:41:12.470 --> 00:41:15.190
with our GPS survey, so
it's a really solid dataset

00:41:15.190 --> 00:41:17.470
to compare with.

00:41:17.470 --> 00:41:19.540
There's a campaign,
an airborne campaign,

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:22.860
called Oppression IceBridge
that flies a laser altimeter

00:41:22.860 --> 00:41:25.430
from an aircraft, and they've
actually flown this circle

00:41:25.430 --> 00:41:26.730
several times.

00:41:26.730 --> 00:41:29.550
So we're able to take our
ground data from the pink line,

00:41:29.550 --> 00:41:32.320
especially around this 88
south arc, and compare it

00:41:32.320 --> 00:41:34.190
with their data from
an airplane,

00:41:34.190 --> 00:41:37.320
and then compare the airplane
data to the data from space.

00:41:37.320 --> 00:41:39.970
So it's sort of a nested
calibration approach.

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:42.510
We just surveyed this
little 300 kilometers,

00:41:42.510 --> 00:41:46.340
but if we use our 300 kilometers
to prove out the aircraft data,

00:41:46.340 --> 00:41:48.650
then we can use that
aircraft data to look

00:41:48.650 --> 00:41:54.040
at an even larger scale,
all to assess ICESat-2.

00:41:54.040 --> 00:41:55.710
So here's what it looks
like when you're cruising

00:41:55.710 --> 00:41:58.440
around at 88 south with 3
of your closest friends.

00:41:58.440 --> 00:41:59.740
We had tract vehicle here.

00:41:59.740 --> 00:42:01.460
We had a big long sled behind us

00:42:01.460 --> 00:42:03.150
that had pretty much
everything we needed

00:42:03.150 --> 00:42:05.660
for the next couple
weeks we were out there.

00:42:05.660 --> 00:42:07.050
We had two of these vehicles.

00:42:07.050 --> 00:42:10.270
You guys might be able to see
these yellow blobs on here.

00:42:10.270 --> 00:42:11.570
Those are our tents.

00:42:11.570 --> 00:42:14.220
We just left them set
up right on the surface.

00:42:14.220 --> 00:42:17.280
And this is pretty typical of
what it looks like down there.

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:19.820
It's pretty flat, right?

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:22.330
You see some little
bumps, little ridges here.

00:42:22.330 --> 00:42:25.010
These are little
snowdrifts called sastrugi.

00:42:25.010 --> 00:42:27.970
But big picture,
it's pretty flat.

00:42:27.970 --> 00:42:30.140
If you take a look
at what the --

00:42:30.140 --> 00:42:32.990
I think I got to
go forward two --

00:42:32.990 --> 00:42:36.200
what the data actually look
like, here's a similar plot

00:42:36.200 --> 00:42:37.500
to what we saw before.

00:42:37.500 --> 00:42:40.150
Here's elevation on this
axis, distance on that one.

00:42:40.150 --> 00:42:41.950
We went over this giant hill.

00:42:41.950 --> 00:42:44.370
It was like 300 feet high.

00:42:44.370 --> 00:42:46.370
But it was like 100 miles long.

00:42:46.370 --> 00:42:48.170
I mean, you would have no idea
that there's a hill there.

00:42:48.170 --> 00:42:49.720
It's so subtle.

00:42:49.720 --> 00:42:51.830
[laughter] But when you
look at the whole arc,

00:42:51.830 --> 00:42:54.410
all the way around 300
kilometers, this is the kind

00:42:54.410 --> 00:42:55.710
of typography you see.

00:42:55.710 --> 00:42:59.070
It's one of the flattest places
on the ice sheet down there.

00:42:59.070 --> 00:43:04.440
The other experiment we left out
there are called corner cubes.

00:43:04.440 --> 00:43:09.270
So comparing against our
reference GPS data gives you a

00:43:09.270 --> 00:43:11.540
sense of elevation,
how good are we doing

00:43:11.540 --> 00:43:13.450
in our elevation measurement.

00:43:13.450 --> 00:43:16.880
What these do is let us test
out how we're doing in terms

00:43:16.880 --> 00:43:19.180
of assigning a latitude
and a longitude.

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:21.970
There's a little plastic
cap we bought at Home Depot,

00:43:21.970 --> 00:43:23.270
drilled a hole in it,

00:43:23.270 --> 00:43:25.630
and there's a little
piece of glass in there.

00:43:25.630 --> 00:43:28.340
Now, the facets and
the edges on that piece

00:43:28.340 --> 00:43:29.700
of glass are optimized

00:43:29.700 --> 00:43:34.140
to reflect green light
back to the space craft.

00:43:34.140 --> 00:43:37.070
When we put these poles in,
we surveyed the location

00:43:37.070 --> 00:43:39.870
of these poles super accurately
with our GPS to be good

00:43:39.870 --> 00:43:41.540
to about a centimeter.

00:43:41.540 --> 00:43:43.680
And these little
pieces of glass in here,

00:43:43.680 --> 00:43:46.790
corner cube retro reflectors,
bounces that light back

00:43:46.790 --> 00:43:48.230
to the space craft,
and we should be able

00:43:48.230 --> 00:43:50.600
to pick these up in our data.

00:43:50.600 --> 00:43:54.670
So we should be able to uniquely
say, oh, this is pole 209,

00:43:54.670 --> 00:43:58.020
and our data processing
assigns it a latitude,

00:43:58.020 --> 00:43:59.530
a longitude, and an elevation.

00:43:59.530 --> 00:44:02.510
But we have an individual
check, an independent check,

00:44:02.510 --> 00:44:07.260
on the latitude, the longitude,
and the elevation of about 40

00:44:07.260 --> 00:44:08.560
of these little poles
that we left

00:44:08.560 --> 00:44:11.090
out in the middle
of the ice sheet.

00:44:11.090 --> 00:44:14.700
So the GPS data by itself
lets you check elevation,

00:44:14.700 --> 00:44:17.970
but surveying specific known
targets lets you check the

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:20.110
latitude and the
longitude, as well.

00:44:20.110 --> 00:44:23.720
Another way you might think
of doing it is hunting

00:44:23.720 --> 00:44:25.400
through our data
until you find data

00:44:25.400 --> 00:44:27.070
that passes over this building.

00:44:27.070 --> 00:44:29.330
We know exactly where
this building is.

00:44:29.330 --> 00:44:31.130
We know exactly how high it is.

00:44:31.130 --> 00:44:32.890
You can go into the
ICESat-2 data and say, well,

00:44:32.890 --> 00:44:35.360
what did ICESat-2 think about
the height of this building

00:44:35.360 --> 00:44:38.010
and the location of the
edges of the building.

00:44:38.010 --> 00:44:40.400
This is a finer measurement
than using a building,

00:44:40.400 --> 00:44:41.860
because this corner
cube is about the size

00:44:41.860 --> 00:44:44.580
of your fingernail and
we know its position

00:44:44.580 --> 00:44:46.530
to better than a centimeter.

00:44:46.530 --> 00:44:47.940
I'm not sure if you
could get positions

00:44:47.940 --> 00:44:50.150
of GSA buildings
to a centimeter.

00:44:50.150 --> 00:44:52.310
If they have it, they
probably don't give it

00:44:52.310 --> 00:44:54.620
out to people, I would guess.

00:44:54.620 --> 00:44:55.920
Anyway, so yeah.

00:44:55.920 --> 00:44:58.490
That was a nice day to be out
on the ice sheet, blue sky.

00:44:58.490 --> 00:44:59.790
Blue on the top.

00:44:59.790 --> 00:45:01.090
White on the bottom.

00:45:01.090 --> 00:45:03.860
Pretty typical of what
it looks like down there.

00:45:03.860 --> 00:45:06.390
Yeah, so for NASA
studying the cryosphere,

00:45:06.390 --> 00:45:07.780
the future really is here.

00:45:07.780 --> 00:45:09.740
We've got two new missions.

00:45:09.740 --> 00:45:13.880
ICESat-2 has a required
lifetime,

00:45:13.880 --> 00:45:15.510
design lifetime of three years.

00:45:15.510 --> 00:45:18.490
We have fuel on board to go
a whole lot longer than that.

00:45:18.490 --> 00:45:21.150
And so far, the data
look really, really good.

00:45:21.150 --> 00:45:23.730
GRACE-Follow-On had
some initial hiccoughs

00:45:23.730 --> 00:45:25.600
in getting their
systems turned on.

00:45:25.600 --> 00:45:28.600
They had to switch from their
A-side instruments to some

00:45:28.600 --> 00:45:29.900
of their B-side instruments,

00:45:29.900 --> 00:45:31.490
but they started
collecting science data again

00:45:31.490 --> 00:45:34.140
about two weeks ago, about
the same time that we did.

00:45:34.140 --> 00:45:37.240
And hopefully, they'll get
their processing sorted out

00:45:37.240 --> 00:45:40.360
and start putting out
some good data, as well.

00:45:40.360 --> 00:45:43.850
Our data from NASA, from both
GRACE-Follow-On and ICESat-2,

00:45:43.850 --> 00:45:45.480
freely available to the public.

00:45:45.480 --> 00:45:48.070
We have a period where we
do checkout and calibration,

00:45:48.070 --> 00:45:49.850
but after that, it
goes to data centers

00:45:49.850 --> 00:45:51.750
that are open to the world.

00:45:51.750 --> 00:45:53.770
Our data center's
called the National Snow

00:45:53.770 --> 00:45:55.070
and Ice Data Center.

00:45:55.070 --> 00:45:56.930
You didn't know that we had
one of those, but we do.

00:45:56.930 --> 00:45:58.300
[laughter] It's in
Boulder, Colorado,

00:45:58.300 --> 00:46:01.340
and if you're interested
in cryospheric data,

00:46:01.340 --> 00:46:04.030
like that from ICESat or
ICESat-2, you can get it there.

00:46:04.030 --> 00:46:06.520
Anybody can.

00:46:06.520 --> 00:46:09.860
Typically the time from date
of data collection to the date

00:46:09.860 --> 00:46:13.710
that you can get it at the
data center is about 40 days.

00:46:13.710 --> 00:46:16.060
We're still in our
beginning phases.

00:46:16.060 --> 00:46:22.330
We just turned the laser on
for the first time 35 days ago.

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:26.600
So but by January, we should be
into pretty normal operations.

00:46:26.600 --> 00:46:29.320
And all of you now are
super excited about ICESat-2

00:46:29.320 --> 00:46:31.670
and looking at your
house from space.

00:46:31.670 --> 00:46:32.980
[laughter] You can do it there.

00:46:32.980 --> 00:46:34.900
National Snow and
Ice Data Center.

00:46:34.900 --> 00:46:37.110
That's all I had, and I'm happy

00:46:37.110 --> 00:46:38.410
to take whatever
questions people have.

00:46:38.410 --> 00:46:40.210
Thanks very much for coming.

