00:46:59.210 --> 00:47:00.510
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: Thanks.

00:47:00.510 --> 00:47:01.810
Thank you very much
for that presentation.

00:47:01.810 --> 00:47:03.660
I'm interested also
in other ways

00:47:03.660 --> 00:47:05.930
of acquiring ground
[inaudible] or --

00:47:05.930 --> 00:47:09.030
and the work that you
actually did are available

00:47:09.030 --> 00:47:13.560
to use earlier data from
known points in the Antarctic

00:47:13.560 --> 00:47:17.540
and [inaudible] to
check other places?

00:47:17.540 --> 00:47:19.540
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Right, so
the question was, if we're --

00:47:19.540 --> 00:47:20.840
if I can paraphrase --

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:24.430
are we able to use data
collected earlier from places

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:27.070
like Greenland or
Antarctica or other places

00:47:27.070 --> 00:47:30.200
to check the quality
of the ICESat-2 data?

00:47:30.200 --> 00:47:32.570
And the answer is, sometimes.

00:47:32.570 --> 00:47:35.020
Greenland and Antarctica
do change through time.

00:47:35.020 --> 00:47:37.980
We know that they're changing
especially close to the edges.

00:47:37.980 --> 00:47:40.480
If you had data collected from
the middle of the ice sheet,

00:47:40.480 --> 00:47:43.470
which is changing
more slowly, then yes,

00:47:43.470 --> 00:47:45.130
we probably can use that.

00:47:45.130 --> 00:47:47.140
There are places on the earth

00:47:47.140 --> 00:47:51.610
that the rock elevation changes
either slowly or in a known way.

00:47:51.610 --> 00:47:54.480
You get these steady
uplift or subsidence.

00:47:54.480 --> 00:47:56.730
We can use that data as well.

00:47:56.730 --> 00:48:00.800
The piece I didn't mention
about our 88 south traverse is

00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:03.460
that we'll repeat
that survey every year

00:48:03.460 --> 00:48:05.270
that ICESat-2 is on orbit.

00:48:05.270 --> 00:48:07.630
So even if that middle part
of the ice sheet is changing,

00:48:07.630 --> 00:48:11.990
and it probably is, we should
be able to correct for that.

00:48:11.990 --> 00:48:15.130
That part of the ice sheet is
one of the more stable parts.

00:48:15.130 --> 00:48:17.120
The elevation change
there should be less

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:19.070
than a centimeter a year.

00:48:19.070 --> 00:48:21.900
But we should be able
to correct out for that.

00:48:21.900 --> 00:48:25.930
So you could use and you can
use prior data, but you have

00:48:25.930 --> 00:48:28.540
to make sure you account for
how the earth has changed

00:48:28.540 --> 00:48:32.820
between when the data was
first collected and today.

00:48:32.820 --> 00:48:34.120
Yeah, in the back.

00:48:34.120 --> 00:48:35.850
&gt;&gt; Audience Member:
So this is ICESat-2.

00:48:35.850 --> 00:48:39.390
What's the difference
between it and ICESat-1?

00:48:39.390 --> 00:48:40.970
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Question
was, this is ICESat-2.

00:48:40.970 --> 00:48:43.380
What's the difference
between it and ICESat-1.

00:48:43.380 --> 00:48:44.680
Whole bunch of good stuff.

00:48:44.680 --> 00:48:48.650
So ICESat-1 was on
orbit from 2003 to 2009.

00:48:48.650 --> 00:48:52.510
It was a single beam altimeter,
so it just had one spot.

00:48:52.510 --> 00:48:54.060
And its spot was pretty big.

00:48:54.060 --> 00:48:56.830
It was about 70 meters
in diameter.

00:48:56.830 --> 00:49:00.060
That laser fired about
40 times a second,

00:49:00.060 --> 00:49:03.090
so you'd get a footprint,
70 meter footprint

00:49:03.090 --> 00:49:05.660
about every 150 meters
along track.

00:49:05.660 --> 00:49:07.940
So you'd get one giant spot.

00:49:07.940 --> 00:49:10.990
Another 100 meters later,
you'd get another giant spot.

00:49:10.990 --> 00:49:14.900
And so for sea ice that
was really difficult to use

00:49:14.900 --> 00:49:17.320
because we couldn't detect
those individual leads

00:49:17.320 --> 00:49:21.390
that are sometimes a lot
smaller than 70 meters.

00:49:21.390 --> 00:49:23.750
And for ice sheets,
what would happen is

00:49:23.750 --> 00:49:27.980
with the big footprints
and the single track,

00:49:27.980 --> 00:49:30.950
we had a hard time
correcting for slope effects.

00:49:30.950 --> 00:49:34.800
So imagine if this room wasn't
flat, but it was tilted,

00:49:34.800 --> 00:49:37.480
and you're ranging to
this tilted surface,

00:49:37.480 --> 00:49:40.500
and you're getting an average
measurement over that slope.

00:49:40.500 --> 00:49:43.730
It was pretty hard to tease
out what's just an effect

00:49:43.730 --> 00:49:47.330
of the surface slope and what's
an effect of elevation change.

00:49:47.330 --> 00:49:49.550
That map of Greenland
I showed at the outset

00:49:49.550 --> 00:49:52.630
that had the color
codes along the edges,

00:49:52.630 --> 00:49:56.270
showing that there were changes
at the edges, we were able

00:49:56.270 --> 00:49:58.240
to detect those changes
because they were on the order

00:49:58.240 --> 00:49:59.540
of like, 10 meters a year.

00:49:59.540 --> 00:50:02.260
They were pretty big differences

00:50:02.260 --> 00:50:05.100
from each time ICESat
would go pass.

00:50:05.100 --> 00:50:07.620
But with ICESat-2, we'll
have these six beams

00:50:07.620 --> 00:50:09.490
that will let us take care
of those slope effects.

00:50:09.490 --> 00:50:12.210
They'll let us find those
leads much easier in sea ice,

00:50:12.210 --> 00:50:14.470
and should give us a
way more refined picture

00:50:14.470 --> 00:50:16.050
of how things are changing.

00:50:16.050 --> 00:50:18.240
But we learned a ton from
the first ICESat mission

00:50:18.240 --> 00:50:20.950
that really went into
designing ICESat-2.

00:50:22.260 --> 00:50:23.560
Yeah?

00:50:23.560 --> 00:50:24.860
&gt;&gt; Audience Member:
[inaudible] the photons

00:50:24.860 --> 00:50:26.910
that are transmitted
and make it back?

00:50:26.910 --> 00:50:28.670
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: The question
was what percent of the photons

00:50:28.670 --> 00:50:31.020
that are transmitted
make it back?

00:50:31.020 --> 00:50:36.520
To round it off to the first
ten significant figures, zero.

00:50:36.520 --> 00:50:39.320
[laughter] So we send out
about 300 trillion photons

00:50:39.320 --> 00:50:42.080
in each pulse, and we
get about one back.

00:50:42.080 --> 00:50:45.270
So it's about 1 part
in 300 trillion.

00:50:45.270 --> 00:50:46.570
So it's -- yeah,
you might say, oh!

00:50:46.570 --> 00:50:50.520
Well, all those wasted
photons are going for nothing.

00:50:50.520 --> 00:50:51.820
[laughter] Which is true.

00:50:51.820 --> 00:50:55.550
But what happens is
the beam spreads.

00:50:55.550 --> 00:50:57.620
There's some beam
divergence to it.

00:50:57.620 --> 00:51:00.250
And so the beam gets larger
and larger, it comes down.

00:51:00.250 --> 00:51:02.430
It's 17 meters when
it hits the earth.

00:51:02.430 --> 00:51:05.550
The earth doesn't reflect all
of the light back towards you.

00:51:05.550 --> 00:51:07.680
Some of the light's
going to go left or right

00:51:07.680 --> 00:51:09.140
or forward or backward.

00:51:09.140 --> 00:51:11.560
Clouds scatter a
lot of it, as well.

00:51:11.560 --> 00:51:13.750
And our field of view

00:51:13.750 --> 00:51:17.940
up in space is an 80
centimeter diameter telescope.

00:51:17.940 --> 00:51:21.000
So the field of view on the
ground is about 45 meters.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:24.340
So we're only detecting photons
that essentially go straight

00:51:24.340 --> 00:51:26.050
down and straight back again.

00:51:26.050 --> 00:51:27.700
A little to the left,
a little to the right,

00:51:27.700 --> 00:51:29.470
and we'll never see them.

00:51:29.470 --> 00:51:32.470
But yeah, most of
those are lost.

00:51:32.470 --> 00:51:34.440
Yeah, way in the back.

00:51:34.440 --> 00:51:36.080
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: If you're
typically getting one or two

00:51:36.080 --> 00:51:37.740
or three photons counted,

00:51:37.740 --> 00:51:40.280
how many do you get
on the corner cubes?

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:41.580
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yeah.

00:51:41.580 --> 00:51:44.010
So those corner cubes,
we don't know yet.

00:51:44.010 --> 00:51:46.100
I've poked around a little bit
in the data looking for them,

00:51:46.100 --> 00:51:48.290
but it's kind of a
needle in a haystack.

00:51:48.290 --> 00:51:50.770
Our geolocation, if you will,

00:51:50.770 --> 00:51:53.840
how precisely we can assign
a latitude, a longitude,

00:51:53.840 --> 00:51:58.450
and a height, we're sort of on
version 1.1 of that algorithm,

00:51:58.450 --> 00:51:59.750
and we keep tuning it.

00:51:59.750 --> 00:52:01.720
So I haven't found
any data for it yet.

00:52:01.720 --> 00:52:05.190
We think they'll be on the
order of about 20 or 25.

00:52:05.190 --> 00:52:07.120
So it should look,
like, really bright,

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:08.780
compared to everything
around it.

00:52:08.780 --> 00:52:11.550
And I put them up on poles that
were anywhere between a meter

00:52:11.550 --> 00:52:13.840
to two meters above the surface.

00:52:13.840 --> 00:52:15.290
So if you're zoomed
in far enough,

00:52:15.290 --> 00:52:16.590
you should see the flat ground,

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:19.260
and then this super bright thing
two meters above the surface.

00:52:19.260 --> 00:52:22.400
And that'll be the corner cube.

00:52:22.400 --> 00:52:23.940
Yeah. Yeah?

00:52:23.940 --> 00:52:27.420
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: You made a
very brief allusion to forestry.

00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:28.720
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yes.

00:52:28.720 --> 00:52:30.880
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: And from
a climate change perspective,

00:52:30.880 --> 00:52:32.860
forest loss is probably
pretty --

00:52:32.860 --> 00:52:37.280
in the same order of
magnitude as ice loss.

00:52:37.280 --> 00:52:38.580
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yeah.

00:52:38.580 --> 00:52:41.570
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: Is there
any formal process put in place

00:52:41.570 --> 00:52:44.660
to have [inaudible] forests
management people look

00:52:44.660 --> 00:52:45.960
at this data?

00:52:45.960 --> 00:52:47.260
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yeah,

00:52:47.260 --> 00:52:49.440
we actually do have a data
product design that's the --

00:52:49.440 --> 00:52:52.000
we call it vegetation
canopy height.

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:54.890
So we have algorithms in
place from simulated data

00:52:54.890 --> 00:52:57.190
to detect the ground below
the canopy, if we can,

00:52:57.190 --> 00:53:00.410
and then the top of the canopy
and take that difference.

00:53:00.410 --> 00:53:04.810
And that should let terrestrial
ecology folks get at biomass

00:53:04.810 --> 00:53:07.680
of forests in different places.

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:11.750
We're not designed to do super
well at that measurement.

00:53:11.750 --> 00:53:15.650
And the limitation
for us is two-fold.

00:53:15.650 --> 00:53:18.460
One, if the canopy is really,
really dense, like you might get

00:53:18.460 --> 00:53:21.470
in Brazil, some triple
canopy rainforests,

00:53:21.470 --> 00:53:23.210
we just won't get any
photons down through

00:53:23.210 --> 00:53:24.640
to the ground and back again.

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:26.200
So we'll measure
the top super well,

00:53:26.200 --> 00:53:28.420
but we won't know
where the ground is.

00:53:28.420 --> 00:53:30.760
On the other end of the
spectrum is a lone tree

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:33.750
out in a field somewhere,
you know?

00:53:33.750 --> 00:53:35.960
And the canopy isn't
dense enough,

00:53:35.960 --> 00:53:37.860
you don't get enough
data to say, all right,

00:53:37.860 --> 00:53:40.360
here's a reliable measurement
of what the tree height is.

00:53:40.360 --> 00:53:42.960
We'll get the ground
super well in that case,

00:53:42.960 --> 00:53:44.260
but not the tree height.

00:53:44.260 --> 00:53:46.810
So there's a sweet
spot for us of forests

00:53:46.810 --> 00:53:50.790
like a deciduous forests,
we should do just fine.

00:53:50.790 --> 00:53:54.480
And then building up data
through time, leaf on, leaf off,

00:53:54.480 --> 00:53:55.940
maybe get a good measurement

00:53:55.940 --> 00:53:57.740
of when the leaves
are on, of the top.

00:53:57.740 --> 00:53:59.730
You get a better measurement of
the ground when leaves are off.

00:53:59.730 --> 00:54:02.660
You put those two together,
now you're in business.

00:54:02.660 --> 00:54:04.530
&gt;&gt; Audience Member:
Yeah, and then also,

00:54:04.530 --> 00:54:05.920
from a climate change
perspective,

00:54:05.920 --> 00:54:11.000
is the aggregate loss of
course, is crucially important

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:15.050
and it looks like that data
ought to be able to help them.

00:54:15.050 --> 00:54:16.350
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yeah.

00:54:16.350 --> 00:54:17.650
It -- [inaudible] absolutely.

00:54:17.650 --> 00:54:20.070
And we do have a couple of
terrestrial ecology folks

00:54:20.070 --> 00:54:23.030
on our science team that are
working towards exactly that.

00:54:23.030 --> 00:54:25.310
We didn't know how well we
would do over forests for them,

00:54:25.310 --> 00:54:26.910
because we're not
really optimized for it.

00:54:26.910 --> 00:54:28.210
It's the wrong wavelength

00:54:28.210 --> 00:54:31.140
and a few other differences
that they'd prefer.

00:54:31.140 --> 00:54:32.960
But it's there and
it's not going

00:54:32.960 --> 00:54:35.400
to be perfect, but
it'll be helpful.

00:54:35.400 --> 00:54:36.700
Yeah?

00:54:36.700 --> 00:54:38.000
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: Are
you able to get any data

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:40.390
on the changes of
the permafrost?

00:54:40.390 --> 00:54:43.040
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: The question
was, are we able to get data

00:54:43.040 --> 00:54:45.730
on changes in the permafrost?

00:54:45.730 --> 00:54:47.830
Yeah, we certainly should.

00:54:47.830 --> 00:54:50.640
Lots of areas, permafrost
is melting.

00:54:50.640 --> 00:54:54.080
And what you see when that
permafrost is two things,

00:54:54.080 --> 00:54:57.810
the surface goes down because
the ice that's in there melts

00:54:57.810 --> 00:55:01.010
and returns to the water
table or to the ocean.

00:55:01.010 --> 00:55:03.260
And two, you get ponding.

00:55:03.260 --> 00:55:05.500
So we'll be able to
measure the heights

00:55:05.500 --> 00:55:06.990
of those water bodies
pretty well.

00:55:06.990 --> 00:55:10.540
We'll be able to tell when
something has gone from wet

00:55:10.540 --> 00:55:13.410
to dry or dry to wet,
in the case of melting.

00:55:13.410 --> 00:55:17.070
We don't have a data product
specifically for permafrost,

00:55:17.070 --> 00:55:19.990
but we have one person on
the team who's interested

00:55:19.990 --> 00:55:22.700
in that aspect, and that's
kind of his main focus,

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:25.270
is trying to measure
permafrost changes.

00:55:25.270 --> 00:55:28.220
So we think we should be able to
do something for them, as well.

00:55:29.340 --> 00:55:30.640
Yeah, in the back?

00:55:30.640 --> 00:55:31.940
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: Why are
you guys using green light

00:55:31.940 --> 00:55:33.810
and not a different --

00:55:33.810 --> 00:55:35.110
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann:
Different wavelength?

00:55:35.110 --> 00:55:36.410
&gt;&gt; Audience Member:
What's the reasoning?

00:55:36.410 --> 00:55:37.710
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yeah.

00:55:37.710 --> 00:55:39.010
So the question is, why do
we use green light as opposed

00:55:39.010 --> 00:55:40.310
to any other wavelength.

00:55:40.310 --> 00:55:42.620
The first ICESat
used infrared light.

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:46.210
It turns out infrared
lasers are more efficient

00:55:46.210 --> 00:55:49.300
at taking electrical energy
and turning it into light,

00:55:49.300 --> 00:55:51.460
which is a consideration.

00:55:51.460 --> 00:55:52.760
We ended up choosing green

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:56.600
to optimize the overall energy
efficiency of the whole design.

00:55:56.600 --> 00:55:58.460
So when you're making
green laser light,

00:55:58.460 --> 00:56:00.680
you're essentially
taking infrared light

00:56:00.680 --> 00:56:03.860
and doubling its frequency
and you have a loss there,

00:56:03.860 --> 00:56:05.280
as well, a pretty big one.

00:56:05.280 --> 00:56:08.600
But on the detection side,
the detectors in the green are

00:56:08.600 --> 00:56:13.340
about 15% efficient, whereas
the detectors in infrared, A,

00:56:13.340 --> 00:56:16.870
weren't space qualified
yet, and B,

00:56:16.870 --> 00:56:19.540
were about a half
of 1% efficient.

00:56:19.540 --> 00:56:23.030
So we got about an order
of magnitude or two better

00:56:23.030 --> 00:56:24.630
on the detection side,

00:56:24.630 --> 00:56:27.830
even though we had this
penalty on the transmit side.

00:56:27.830 --> 00:56:29.130
But you put those two together,

00:56:29.130 --> 00:56:32.280
and it made green a
better choice for us.

00:56:33.670 --> 00:56:34.970
Yeah?

00:56:34.970 --> 00:56:36.270
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: The
National Weather Service uses

00:56:36.270 --> 00:56:38.240
about 8,000 volunteers
to measure snow depth.

00:56:38.240 --> 00:56:39.540
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yeah.

00:56:39.540 --> 00:56:40.870
&gt;&gt; Audience Member: What's
the implications of this

00:56:40.870 --> 00:56:42.970
for that measurement
of snow depth?

00:56:42.970 --> 00:56:44.270
&gt;&gt; Dr. Tom Neumann: Yeah.

00:56:44.270 --> 00:56:47.860
So the question was the National
-- National Weather Service?

00:56:47.860 --> 00:56:50.870
Yeah. Uses volunteers to measure
snow depth all over the place.

00:56:50.870 --> 00:56:53.620
What can ICESat-2 do for them?

00:56:53.620 --> 00:56:54.920
It's a good question.

00:56:54.920 --> 00:56:56.410
So we have our six beams.

00:56:56.410 --> 00:57:00.950
They repeat every 91 days, so
we should go through a place

00:57:00.950 --> 00:57:03.260
like Wisconsin, where
I'm from, in the summer,

00:57:03.260 --> 00:57:04.560
and you get a good measurement

00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:06.660
of the surface without
snow on it.

00:57:06.660 --> 00:57:10.200
And then we come through 91 days
later, maybe it's October yes,

00:57:10.200 --> 00:57:12.690
it already started
snowing there.

00:57:12.690 --> 00:57:14.520
So if you're there after a
snowfall, you should be able

00:57:14.520 --> 00:57:16.750
to take those two
elevation measurements,

00:57:16.750 --> 00:57:19.520
take the difference,
and get the snow depth.

00:57:19.520 --> 00:57:21.570
It's just a height,
and as I understand it,

00:57:21.570 --> 00:57:24.440
what a lot of their interested
in is snow water equivalent,

00:57:24.440 --> 00:57:26.170
how much water is in there.

00:57:26.170 --> 00:57:28.870
But at least getting that height
difference between snow on

00:57:28.870 --> 00:57:31.880
and snow off should
be useful for them.

00:57:31.880 --> 00:57:36.750
There's a group called -- ooh,
their mission is called SnowX

00:57:36.750 --> 00:57:40.580
and they're working
to come up with a way

00:57:40.580 --> 00:57:43.820
to measure snow water
equivalent from space

00:57:43.820 --> 00:57:45.120
for about a decade from now.

00:57:45.120 --> 00:57:46.840
So they're just at
the beginning.

00:57:46.840 --> 00:57:49.200
So they're super interested
in our data to get a map

00:57:49.200 --> 00:57:51.690
of what snow depth is like.

00:57:51.690 --> 00:57:53.850
A place like Wisconsin,
it's relatively easy

00:57:53.850 --> 00:57:56.560
because it's farm fields,
it's relatively flat.

00:57:56.560 --> 00:57:59.260
A place like the Rocky
Mountains or Sierra Nevada,

00:57:59.260 --> 00:58:03.200
where there's steep slopes,
is going to be a lot harder

00:58:03.200 --> 00:58:06.180
because you're pointing and
your geolocation have to be

00:58:06.180 --> 00:58:09.410
that much better to know if you
were -- on some steep slope,

00:58:09.410 --> 00:58:11.770
to know if you were here or you
were here, because you'd say,

00:58:11.770 --> 00:58:15.030
okay, this snow pack is one
meter or it's ten meters.

00:58:15.030 --> 00:58:19.690
Because just because that slope
of that ground is so severe.

00:58:19.690 --> 00:58:21.690
Yeah. We're not optimized
for it, but we should be able

00:58:21.690 --> 00:58:22.990
to help there, as well.

00:58:22.990 --> 00:58:25.290
At least in some circumstances.

